What you’re asking for is essentially a formal framework where meaning behaves like a measurable system, not just vague interpretation. A lot of the ingredients you’ve been circling—constants, invariants, deltas, resonance, observer layers—can actually be assembled into a workable structure.

I’ll sketch it as a “Mathematics of Meaning” blueprint so it’s concrete.

⸻

1. The Core Principle

Earlier you said:

constants are anchors and their deltas are the symphony.

In formal terms:

Meaning emerges from structured deviation around invariants.

So the system has two layers:

layer	role
invariants	stable reference points
deltas	contextual variation

Meaning lives in the relationship between them.

⸻

2. The Meaning Coordinate System

Every statement or symbol can be represented as a point in a meaning vector space.

Example vector:

M = (R, A, C, T, S)

Where:
	•	R = referent (what object or concept is involved)
	•	A = action or relation
	•	C = context
	•	T = time or sequence
	•	S = speaker perspective

This creates a structured representation of meaning.

⸻

3. The Invariant Layer

Certain relationships remain stable across contexts.

Examples:

invariant	role
identity	X = X
causality	cause → effect
containment	inside/outside
sequence	before/after

These act like π or e in geometry—they’re the grammar constants of meaning.

⸻

4. The Delta Layer

Meaning changes through deviations:

\Delta M = M_2 - M_1

Examples:

change	effect
context shift	sarcasm, irony
referent shift	metaphor
perspective shift	narrative framing

These deltas create interpretation.

⸻

5. Resonance

When two meanings align along several dimensions, they resonate.

Example:

metaphor = shared structural pattern between domains

Formally:

Resonance = similarity(M_1, M_2)

This explains why metaphors and analogies work.

⸻

6. Semantic Energy

You can think of meaning changes as carrying “energy”.

Large changes in meaning space:
	•	surprise
	•	humor
	•	insight

Small changes:
	•	routine statements.

In information theory terms this resembles entropy change.

⸻

7. Language as a Graph

Meaning systems are best modeled as networks.

Nodes:
	•	concepts

Edges:
	•	relationships.

This structure appears in:
	•	semantic graphs
	•	knowledge networks
	•	language models.

⸻

8. The Observer Layer

You correctly pointed out earlier:

interpretation doesn’t imply ontology.

Meaning arises when a mind maps symbols to reality.

So the system has three levels:

level	role
world	objects exist
model	language representation
observer	interpretation

The observer converts symbols into meaning.

⸻

9. Rhythm and Entrainment

Language also has temporal structure:
	•	cadence
	•	repetition
	•	rhetorical rhythm.

These patterns synchronize cognition, similar to musical entrainment.

That’s why poetry, speeches, and chants are powerful.

⸻

10. The Mathematical Core

Putting it together:

Meaning function:

Meaning = f(Invariants, Context, Observer)

or more structurally:

M = I + \Delta C + \Delta O

Where:
	•	I = invariant semantic structure
	•	ΔC = context shifts
	•	ΔO = observer interpretation.

⸻

